=== Pixel Slate ===
{{Main|Pixel Slate}}

The Pixel Slate, a {{convert|12.3|in|cm|abbr=on}} [[2-in-1 laptop|2-in-1 tablet and laptop]], was announced by Google in New York City on October 9, 2018,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/pixel-3-google-hub-and-pixel-slate-everything-google-just-announced/ |title=Pixel 3, Google Home Hub and Pixel Slate: Everything Google Just Announced |first1=Lori |last1=Grunan |first2=Alina |last2=Bradford |date=October 9, 2018 |publisher=CNET}}</ref> alongside the Pixel 3 and 3 XL. The Pixel Slate includes two USB-C ports but omits the headphone jack. The device runs [[ChromeOS]] on [[Intel]] [[Kaby Lake]] processors, with options ranging from a [[Celeron]] on the low end to an i7 on the high end. In June 2019, Google announced it will not further develop the product line, and cancelled two models that were under development.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.computerworld.com/article/3404206/googles-officially-done-making-its-own-tablets.html |title=Google's officially done making its own tablets |first=J. R. |last=Raphael |date=June 20, 2019 |website=Computerworld}}</ref>

=== Pixel Tablet ===
{{main|Pixel Tablet}}
The Pixel Tablet was announced by Google at [[Google I/O#2022|I/O 2022]]. It comes with a stand, similar to that of a [[Google Nest (smart speakers)#Home Hub / Nest Hub|Home Hub]]; however, it is detachable.<ref>{{Cite web |title=The new Google Pixel Tablet, coming in 2023 |url=https://store.google.com/intl/en/ideas/articles/new-pixel-tablet/ |access-date=November 27, 2022 |website=Google Store |language=en}}</ref> It was released on June 20, 2023.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Google Pixel Tablet is finally here: Price, specs, features, dock, and more |url=https://www.androidauthority.com/google-pixel-tablet-3163922/ |access-date=May 11, 2023 |website=Android Authority}}</ref>
*Display: 10.95-inch LCD (2560×1600, 16:10 [[aspect ratio]]), 60&nbsp;Hz, 500&nbsp;nits
*Processor: Google Tensor G2
*Storage: 128&nbsp;GB or 256&nbsp;GB; are non-expandable
*Memory: 8&nbsp;GB LPDDR5 RAM
*Camera: Rear and front: 8&nbsp;MP (ƒ/2.0, 1/4" sensor, 1.12&nbsp;μm, 84° FoV) fixed-focus
*Battery: Non-removable 7,020&nbsp;mAh; charges at 15&nbsp;W, both wired and through the dock; No wireless charging supported.
*Materials: Aluminium frame, nano ceramic back, no water/dust resistance
*Colors: Hazel {{Colorbox|#7c817d}}, Porcelain {{Colorbox|#dacfc7}} and Rose {{Colorbox|#e9d0c2}} ; not available in certain areas.
*Operating system: Android 13 with Pixel UI, at least 3 years of software updates and 5 years of security updates

== Laptops ==

=== Chromebook Pixel (2013) ===
{{Main|Chromebook Pixel}}

[[File:Chromebook Pixel (WiFi) open.JPG|thumb|upright|Chromebook Pixel (2013)]]

Google announced the first-generation Chromebook Pixel in a blog post on February 21, 2013.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Chromebook Pixel, for what's next |url=https://chrome.googleblog.com/2013/02/the-chromebook-pixel-for-whats-next.html|access-date=September 2, 2016}}</ref> The laptop includes an SD/multi-card reader, [[Mini DisplayPort]], combination headphone/microphone jack, and two USB 2.0 ports. Some of the device's other features include a backlit keyboard, a "fully clickable etched glass touchpad," integrated stereo speakers, and two built-in microphones.<ref>{{cite web |title=Chromebook Pixel specifications |url=https://support.google.com/chromebook/answer/2762037?hl=en|access-date=September 2, 2016|archive-date=October 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011052035/https://support.google.com/chromebook/answer/2762037?hl=en|url-status=dead}}</ref>

* Display: 12.85" display with 2560×1700 pixel resolution
* Processor: 3rd generation ([[Ivy Bridge (microarchitecture)|Ivy Bridge]]) Intel Core i5 processor
* Storage: 32&nbsp;GB internal storage and 1&nbsp;TB [[Google Drive]] storage for 3 years
* RAM: 4&nbsp;GB
* Battery: 59&nbsp;[[Watt-hour|Wh]]

=== Chromebook Pixel (2015) ===
{{Main|Chromebook Pixel}}

On March 11, 2015, Google announced the second generation of the Chromebook Pixel in a blog post.<ref>{{cite web |title=Meet the updated Chromebook Pixel and the new Google Store |url=https://blog.google/products/chromebooks/meet-updated-chromebook-pixel-and-new/ |access-date=October 22, 2025 |date=March 11, 2015 |first1=Andrew |last1=Bowers}}</ref> The laptop includes two USB-C ports, two USB 3.0 ports, an SD card slot, and a combination headphone/microphone jack. The device also has a backlit keyboard, a "multi-touch, clickable glass touchpad," built-in stereo speakers, and two built-in microphones, among other features.<ref>{{cite web |title=Chromebook Pixel (2015) specifications |url=https://support.google.com/chromebook/answer/6164568|access-date=September 2, 2016|archive-date=October 11, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161011051941/https://support.google.com/chromebook/answer/6164568|url-status=dead}}</ref>

Google discontinued the 2015 Chromebook Pixel on August 29, 2016.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Novet |first1=Jordan |title=Google discontinues the Chromebook Pixel 2 |date=August 30, 2016 |url=https://venturebeat.com/2016/08/29/chromebook-pixel-2-discontinued/ |access-date=September 2, 2016 |archive-date=September 2, 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160902042451/https://venturebeat.com/2016/08/29/chromebook-pixel-2-discontinued/ |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Parker |first1=Peter |title=Google discontinues the Pixel 4 less than 1 year after launch |url=https://theappdevelopers.co.uk/portfolio/google-discontinues-the-pixel-4-nine-months-after-release/|access-date=August 7, 2020|archive-date=June 24, 2021|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210624124125/https://theappdevelopers.co.uk/portfolio/google-discontinues-the-pixel-4-nine-months-after-release/|url-status=dead}}</ref>

* Display: 12.85" display with 2560×1700 pixel resolution
* Processor: 5th generation ([[Broadwell (microarchitecture)|Broadwell]]) Intel Core i5 or i7 processor
* Storage: 32 or 64&nbsp;GB internal storage and 1&nbsp;TB Google Drive storage for 3 years
* RAM: 8 or 16&nbsp;GB
* Battery: 72&nbsp;Wh

=== Pixelbook ===
{{Main|Pixelbook}}

On October 4, 2017, Google launched the first generation of the Pixelbook at its Made by Google 2017 event.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/10/04/google-pixelbook-chromebook/ |title=Google's Pixelbook is a 2-in-1 premium Chromebook |work=Engadget|access-date=October 4, 2017 |language=en-US}}</ref>

* Display: 12.3" display with 2400×1600 pixel resolution (235 PPI)
* Processor: 7th generation ([[Kaby Lake]]) Intel Core i5 or i7 processor
* Storage: 128, 256, or 512&nbsp;GB internal storage
* RAM: 8 or 16&nbsp;GB

=== Pixelbook Go ===
{{main|Pixelbook Go}}

On October 15, 2019, Google announced a mid-range version of the Pixelbook, named the Pixelbook Go, at its Made by Google 2019 event.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/10/15/20908076/google-pixelbook-go-chromebook-photos-video-price-specs-features-hands-on |title=Pixelbook Go: Google finally made a reasonably priced Chromebook |work=[[The Verge]] |last=Bohn |first=Dieter |date=October 15, 2019|access-date=October 16, 2019}}</ref>

* Display: 13.3" display with 1920×1080 pixel resolution (166 ppi) or "Molecular Display" 3840×2160 pixel resolution (331 PPI)
* Processor: 8th generation ([[Kaby Lake#Amber Lake|Amber Lake]]) Intel Core m3, i5 or i7 processor
* Storage: 64, 128, or 256&nbsp;GB internal storage
* RAM: 8 or 16&nbsp;GB
* Battery: 47&nbsp;Wh, 56&nbsp;Wh (Molecular Display)

== Smartwatches ==

=== Pixel Watch ===
{{main|Pixel Watch}}
The Google Pixel Watch is a first-generation wearable made by Google that released in October 2022. It features a circular display. Multiple wristbands for the watch are available on the [[Store.google.com|Google Store]] for purchase.

=== Pixel Watch 2 ===
{{main|Pixel Watch 2}}
The Pixel Watch 2 is a second-generation wearable made by Google that released in October 2023. It features a similar design to the first-generation [[Pixel Watch]]'s circular display. Multiple wristbands for the watch are available on the [[Store.google.com|Google Store]] for purchase.

=== Pixel Watch 3 ===
{{main|Pixel Watch 3}}
The Pixel Watch 3 is a third-generation wearable made by Google that released in August 2024.

=== Pixel Watch 4 ===
{{main|Pixel Watch 4}}
The Pixel Watch 4 is a fourth-generation wearable made by Google, announced in August 2025.

== Accessories ==

=== Pixel Buds ===
{{main|Pixel Buds}}

At Google's October 2017 hardware event, a set of [[wireless communication|wireless]] [[Headphones#Earphones|earbuds]] were unveiled alongside the Pixel 2 smartphones.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://9to5google.com/2017/10/04/google-earphones-assistant-headphones/ |title=Google Pixel Buds: Assistant-enabled Bluetooth neckbuds from Google |last=Li |first=Abner |date=October 4, 2017 |website=[[9to5Google]]|access-date=October 4, 2017}}</ref> The earbuds are designed for phones running Android Marshmallow or higher, and work with [[Google Assistant]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.theverge.com/circuitbreaker/2017/10/4/16401132/google-pixel-buds-wireless-headphones-announced-price-release-date |title=Google's Pixel Buds are the company's first wireless headphones |last=Carman |first=Ashley |date=October 4, 2017 |work=[[The Verge]]|access-date=October 4, 2017}}</ref> In addition to audio playback and answering calls, the earbuds support translation in 40 languages through [[Google Translate]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2017/10/google-pixel-buds-are-wireless-earbuds-that-translate-conversations-in-real-time/ |title=Google Pixel Buds are wireless earbuds that translate conversations in real time |last=Pallandino |first=Valentina |date=October 4, 2017 |work=[[Ars Technica]]|access-date=October 4, 2017}}</ref> The earbuds can auto-pair with the [[Pixel 2]] with the help of the [[Google Assistant]] and "Nearby".<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://9to5google.com/2017/10/04/googles-pixel-buds-use-assistant-to-auto-pair-your-phone-just-like-apples-airpods/ |title=Google's Pixel Buds use Assistant to auto-pair to your phone, just like Apple's AirPods [Update] |date=October 4, 2017 |work=[[9to5Google]]|access-date=February 8, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> The Pixel Buds are available in the colors Just Black, Clearly White and Kinda Blue. The earbuds have a battery capacity of 120&nbsp;mAh, while the charging case that comes with the Pixel Buds have a battery capacity of 620&nbsp;mAh.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web |url=https://store.google.com/product/google_pixel_buds |title=Google Pixel Buds |website=Google Store |language=en-US|access-date=February 8, 2018}}</ref> The earbuds are priced at $159.<ref name=":1" />

A [[Pixel Buds#Second generation|second generation of Pixel Buds]] were released in 2020, omitting the cord between the two earbuds. In June 2021, a mid-range variant of the second-generation earbuds were released as the [[Pixel_Buds#Pixel_Buds_A-Series|Pixel Buds A-Series]].

At the [[Google I/O#2022|2022 Google I/O event]], an enhanced version of the second-generation earbuds was announced and later released in May 2022, as the [[Pixel_Buds#Pixel_Buds_Pro|Pixel Buds Pro]], which featured [[Active noise control|Active Noise Cancellation]] mode, transparency mode, and [[3D audio effect|spatial audio]] (added in a subsequent software update). The "Pro" earbuds are priced at $199.

At Google's 2025 Made by Google event, the [[Pixel Buds#Pixel Buds 2a|Pixel Buds 2a]] were announced.

=== Pixelbook Pen ===
Alongside the launch of the Pixelbook in October 2017, Google announced the Pixelbook Pen, a [[stylus]] to be used with the Pixelbook. It has pressure sensitivity as well as support for [[Google Assistant]]. The Pen is powered by a replaceable [[AAAA battery]] and is priced at US$99.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.engadget.com/2017/10/04/google-pixelbook-pen/ |title=Google's Pixelbook Pen searches for what you circle |work=Engadget|access-date=October 14, 2017 |language=en-US}}</ref>

=== Pixel Stand ===
In October 2018, Google announced the Pixel Stand alongside the Pixel 3 smartphones.<ref name="PixelStandCNet">{{cite web |url=https://www.cnet.com/how-to/pixel-stand-5-things-to-know/ |date=October 22, 2018 |last=Cipriani |first=Jason|access-date=January 4, 2019 |publisher=[[CNET]] |title=Pixel Stand: 5 things to know about Google's wireless charger}}</ref> In addition to standard 5&nbsp;watt [[Qi (standard)|Qi]] wireless charging, the Pixel Stand has wireless 10&nbsp;watt charging using a proprietary technology from Google.<ref name="PixelStandDigitalTrends">{{cite web |url=https://www.digitaltrends.com/cell-phone-accessories-reviews/google-pixel-stand-review/ |date=October 26, 2018 |last=Chokkattu |first=Julian|access-date=January 4, 2019 |work=[[Digital Trends]] |title=Google Pixel Stand Review}}</ref> It also enables a software mode on the Pixel 3 that allows it to act as a [[Smart speaker|smart display]] similar to the [[Google Home Hub]]. In October 2021, alongside the release of the [[Pixel 6]] and [[Pixel 6 Pro]] smartphones, a second-generation Pixel Stand was made to support the phones' new wireless charging speeds of 23 watts.<ref>{{Cite web |date=October 19, 2021 |title=Pixel Stand 2 brings 23W wireless charging to new Pixel 6 and more |url=https://www.trustedreviews.com/news/pixel-stand-2-brings-23w-wireless-charging-to-new-pixel-6-and-more-4174707 |access-date=May 12, 2023 |website=Trusted Reviews |language=en}}</ref>

== Software ==

=== Pixel UI (Pixel Launcher) ===
{{Infobox OS
| name = Pixel Launcher
| screenshot = 
| screenshot_size = 130px
| caption = [[Android 13]] home screen with Pixel Launcher
| developer = [[Google]]
| family = [[Unix-like]] (modified [[Linux kernel]])
